<h2 id="guidelines">Guidelines</h2>
<h3 id="hard-code">Do not hard code values</h3>
<p>Facebook <a href="https://www.slideshare.net/maxdesign/css-oocss-and-smacss/16-FacebookFacebook_blue_261_Unique_colors" target="_blank" rel="noopener">famously</a> had 548 unique colors hard-coded 6,498 times across all their stylesheets. That's a maintenance meltdown! Custom properties are a standard CSS feature that helps you avoid this by defining reusable values. Reference these custom properties instead of hard coding their values. Like this:</p>
<code-sample mode="css" readonly="readonly">
/* Do */
@import "../node_modules/m-/dist/custom-props.css";
#foo \{
  background-color: var(--m-color-gray-2);
}

/* Don't */
#foo \{
  background-color: #dedede;
}
</code-sample>
<p>Go <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/--*" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here</a> to learn more about custom properties and how to use them.</p>
